230
00:13:13,460 --> 00:13:16,395
   to see which scenes they've  
    been assigned to animate.   

231
00:13:16,397 --> 00:13:19,598
   a printout of the animatic   
   shows all the episode shots  

232
00:13:19,600 --> 00:13:21,533
          at a glance.          

233
00:13:22,536 --> 00:13:23,735
     in the art department,     

234
00:13:23,737 --> 00:13:26,338
         construction of        
the episode's costumes and props

235
00:13:26,340 --> 00:13:28,073
        is well underway.       

236
00:13:28,075 --> 00:13:30,409
   to make a few red balloons,  
          for example,          

237
00:13:30,411 --> 00:13:33,411
   the prop makers sculpt one   
     out of molding material    

238
00:13:33,413 --> 00:13:36,481
  and use it to produce a hard, 
         silicone mold.         

239
00:13:36,483 --> 00:13:40,352
 then they pour a thick-setting 
   resin into the mold cavity.  

240
00:13:43,156 --> 00:13:45,623
         after the resin        
     has hardened overnight,    

241
00:13:45,625 --> 00:13:49,194
      they open up the mold     
    and extract the casting.    

242
00:13:56,704 --> 00:13:58,970
        they drill a hole       
        in the bottom...        

243
00:14:02,976 --> 00:14:06,278
   ...dab some glue inside...   

244
00:14:10,183 --> 00:14:12,984
     ...then insert a small,    
         triangular peg,        

245
00:14:12,986 --> 00:14:15,920
            also made           
     of quick-setting resin.    

246
00:14:15,922 --> 00:14:18,790
 this forms the tied balloon end
         of the balloon.        

247
00:14:22,262 --> 00:14:24,830
   now a coat of gray primer.   

248
00:14:25,999 --> 00:14:29,167
 then, once it dries, red paint.

249
00:14:36,610 --> 00:14:38,410
      when the paint dries,     

250
00:14:38,412 --> 00:14:40,679
  they drill another tiny hole  
   at the base of the balloon   

251
00:14:40,681 --> 00:14:42,347
       and insert a strand      

252
00:14:42,349 --> 00:14:45,750
 of flexible copper wire wrapped
        in cotton thread.       

253
00:14:45,752 --> 00:14:47,853
   this is the balloon string.  

254
00:14:51,491 --> 00:14:55,026
  the team of animators shoot   
  several scenes concurrently.  

255
00:14:55,028 --> 00:14:57,028
           therefore,           
    in the puppet department,   

256
00:14:57,030 --> 00:15:00,364
  model makers produce multiple 
   puppets for each character,  

257
00:15:00,366 --> 00:15:03,101
 plus lots of extra body parts. 

258
00:15:07,774 --> 00:15:11,042
   certain puppet body parts,   
    such as hands and wings,    

259
00:15:11,044 --> 00:15:15,046
      are made of silicone      
  with a wire skeleton within.  

260
00:15:15,048 --> 00:15:17,048
     after forming the wire     
            to shape            

261
00:15:17,050 --> 00:15:19,317
          and applying          
    a base coat of silicone,    

262
00:15:19,319 --> 00:15:21,986
    the puppet maker lays it    
       in a two-part mold,      

263
00:15:21,988 --> 00:15:24,656
    then fills both cavities    
         with silicone.         

264
00:15:26,259 --> 00:15:28,727
     she closes the mold...     

265
00:15:28,729 --> 00:15:31,196
     clamps it tightly shut,    

266
00:15:31,198 --> 00:15:34,933
     and leaves the silicone    
        to set overnight.       

267
00:15:37,404 --> 00:15:39,871
          the flexible,         
    wire skeleton at the core   

268
00:15:39,873 --> 00:15:44,075
enables the animator to position
  a hand or wing various ways.  

269
00:15:59,826 --> 00:16:02,160
            narrator:           
    in stop-frame animation,    

270
00:16:02,162 --> 00:16:04,496
   the more movable the puppet  
    and its facial features,    

271
00:16:04,498 --> 00:16:07,499
        the more lifelike       
 the animated character appears.

272
00:16:07,501 --> 00:16:10,101
       the animator moves       
    the puppet incrementally    

273
00:16:10,103 --> 00:16:12,169
   for each frame they shoot,   

274
00:16:12,171 --> 00:16:17,042
   and 25 such frames produce   
  just one second of animation. 

275
00:16:22,582 --> 00:16:24,516
          timmy's torso         

276
00:16:24,518 --> 00:16:27,385
   is a polyurethane-foam core  
     dressed in a wool coat.    

277
00:16:27,387 --> 00:16:29,721
         it has channels        
    for interchangeable wires   

278
00:16:29,723 --> 00:16:32,390
 that support his head and arms.

279
00:16:32,392 --> 00:16:34,392
   his head is made of resin,   

280
00:16:34,394 --> 00:16:37,529
      his arm silicone over     
        a wire skeleton.        

281
00:16:37,531 --> 00:16:39,330
  timmy and his friends' faces  

282
00:16:39,332 --> 00:16:41,733
    can express a wide range    
           of emotions          

283
00:16:41,735 --> 00:16:44,336
             thanks             
   to interchangeable mouths,   

284
00:16:44,338 --> 00:16:46,337
    flexible ears and blinks,   

285
00:16:46,339 --> 00:16:48,339
          an assortment         
     of exchangeable eyelids    

286
00:16:48,341 --> 00:16:51,776
      conveying expressions     
   from wide-eyed to cockeyed.  

287
00:16:53,280 --> 00:16:56,281
  these facial features attach  
       either magnetically      

288
00:16:56,283 --> 00:17:00,519
      or with tacky wax --      
 a flexible, quick-release glue.

289
00:17:01,822 --> 00:17:04,022
   the puppet-maintenance team  
      packs each character      

290
00:17:04,024 --> 00:17:06,157
 and its parts in a travel box, 

291
00:17:06,159 --> 00:17:09,828
  then sends it to the animator 
      on the studio floor.      

292
00:17:09,830 --> 00:17:11,162
        during shooting,        

293
00:17:11,164 --> 00:17:14,832
    the animator changes the    
 facial expressions as required.

294
00:17:14,834 --> 00:17:18,236
  while their work does indeed  
 require great technical skill, 

295
00:17:18,238 --> 00:17:22,106
 the animators are actors who,  
 under the director's guidance, 

296
00:17:22,108 --> 00:17:25,109
         perform through        
 the puppets they bring to life.

297
00:17:25,111 --> 00:17:27,512
     the puppet's legs must     
        be sturdy enough        

298
00:17:27,514 --> 00:17:29,981
      to support the weight     
        of the upper body       

299
00:17:29,983 --> 00:17:31,582
  when the puppet is standing,  

300
00:17:31,584 --> 00:17:33,050
       so the leg skeleton      

301
00:17:33,052 --> 00:17:37,055
 is made of metal rods connected
  with ball-and-socket joints.  

302
00:17:37,057 --> 00:17:40,992
    the feet are metal plates   
    hinged to allow movement.   

303
00:17:40,994 --> 00:17:44,128
     just like the flexible,    
         wire skeletons,        

304
00:17:44,130 --> 00:17:46,264
       this metal skeleton      
      also goes into a mold     

305
00:17:46,266 --> 00:17:48,933
   to be encased in silicone.   

306
00:17:48,935 --> 00:17:51,803
         the arms attach        
 with square-section brass tubes

307
00:17:51,805 --> 00:17:54,039
             so they            
   can be easily interchanged   

308
00:17:54,041 --> 00:17:56,274
        with a few turns        
        of an allen key.        

309
00:17:58,345 --> 00:18:00,745
    certain puppet movements    
        require rigging.        

310
00:18:00,747 --> 00:18:03,147
        a rig is a device       
     that enables animators     

311
00:18:03,149 --> 00:18:05,817
       to raise the puppet      
    off the floor of the set    

312
00:18:05,819 --> 00:18:08,553
to perform jumping and skipping.

313
00:18:11,090 --> 00:18:13,224
          the animator          
     can incrementally lift     

314
00:18:13,226 --> 00:18:16,094
 or lower the rig to any height 
       and lock it there.       

315
00:18:21,367 --> 00:18:24,169
   there are many preparations  
     before shooting begins,    

316
00:18:24,171 --> 00:18:25,503
        such as lighting,       

317
00:18:25,505 --> 00:18:28,573
      puppet positioning...     

318
00:18:28,575 --> 00:18:31,009
        and set dressing.       

319
00:18:33,313 --> 00:18:36,981
   using the animatic playing   
  on a monitor as a reference,  

320
00:18:36,983 --> 00:18:39,618
the director and camera operator
         frame the shot.        

321
00:18:46,393 --> 00:18:49,260
   meanwhile, the set dressers  
      prepare the next set,     

322
00:18:49,262 --> 00:18:51,663
       gathering whatever       
    scenic objects they need    

323
00:18:51,665 --> 00:18:53,632
   from the set-dressing kit.   

324
00:18:58,138 --> 00:18:59,671
    to create these objects,    

325
00:18:59,673 --> 00:19:03,274
 artists first sculpt the shapes
    out of modeling material.   

326
00:19:03,276 --> 00:19:06,010
       they create a mold       
 from which they produce copies 

327
00:19:06,012 --> 00:19:09,413
          in fiberglass         
     or quick-setting resin.    

328
00:19:09,415 --> 00:19:11,783
   then they paint the copies.  

329
00:19:19,158 --> 00:19:21,425
      with the set dressed      
          and approved,         

330
00:19:21,427 --> 00:19:23,094
     the animator can begin.    

331
00:19:23,096 --> 00:19:26,297
    with great care referring   
        to the animatic,        

332
00:19:26,299 --> 00:19:28,400
 he positions the rigged puppet.

333
00:19:34,107 --> 00:19:36,641
then, with the push of a button,
       he shoots a frame,       

334
00:19:36,643 --> 00:19:40,779
     or, in animation lingo,    
        grabs the frame.        

335
00:19:40,781 --> 00:19:44,315
         next, he moves         
    the puppet incrementally    

336
00:19:44,317 --> 00:19:47,152
    and makes slight changes    
     to body positioning...     

337
00:19:49,656 --> 00:19:52,457
   ...and grabs another frame.  

338
00:19:52,459 --> 00:19:57,328
      25 consecutive frames     
 equal one second of animation. 

339
00:19:57,330 --> 00:20:00,598
       the animator's art       
 is knowing how and by how much 

340
00:20:00,600 --> 00:20:03,668
       to move the puppet       
  to create lifelike movement.  

341
00:20:05,271 --> 00:20:07,405
         to get special         
      close-up facial shots     

342
00:20:07,407 --> 00:20:10,275
  that they'll later intercut   
  with the full-body sequence,  

343
00:20:10,277 --> 00:20:12,610
  they sometimes set the puppet 

344
00:20:12,612 --> 00:20:16,514
  on a rig positioned directly  
     in front of the camera.    

345
00:20:19,752 --> 00:20:21,486
once they've shot the animation,

346
00:20:21,488 --> 00:20:23,621
     they take what's called    
           a plate --           

347
00:20:23,623 --> 00:20:27,892
 a shot of the set with puppets,
    props, and rigs removed.    

348
00:20:27,894 --> 00:20:30,628
  they send the plate digitally 
      to the editing suite,     

349
00:20:30,630 --> 00:20:34,098
      where the editor uses     
the visuals to cover up the rig,

350
00:20:34,100 --> 00:20:36,835
     essentially erasing it     
           from view.           

351
00:20:36,837 --> 00:20:39,904
          this process          
    is called compositing --    

352
00:20:39,906 --> 00:20:42,640
          a little bit          
  of behind-the-scenes artistry 

353
00:20:42,642 --> 00:20:46,644
      to create a whole lot     
       of onscreen magic.       

354
00:20:46,646 --> 00:20:48,613
           [ laughs ]           

355
00:20:50,517 --> 00:20:53,251
        [ laughing ] baa!       

356
